{"type":"step-attempt","step":"cross-boundary-invariants","sessionId":"78449729-e9dc-43fe-b867-5d461d293910","outcome":{"verdict":"approved","findingsPath":"specrunner/changes/scope-exceeded-escalation/cross-boundary-invariants-result-001.md","error":null,"toolResult":{"ok":true,"approved":true,"findings":[{"severity":"medium","resolution":"fixable","file":"src/core/step/executor.ts","title":"`verdict:parsed` event emits original toolResult instead of scope-merged persistToolResult","rationale":"Before this change, the implicit invariant held: `verdict:parsed.toolResult` == `state.steps[step][-1].outcome.toolResult`. When a scope breach is synthesized, `persistToolResult` (used in `pushStepResult`) contains the merged scope findings, but the `verdict:parsed` event at line 765 emits `agentResult?.toolResult ?? null` — the pre-synthesis original. As a result, `pipeline-logger.ts` records an escalation verdict with no decision-needed finding in the event payload, making scope-triggered escalations appear as unexplained escalations in diagnostic logs. Pipeline routing is unaffected (routing uses `verdict`, which is correctly `escalation`); `getOpenDecisionFindings` and the decision-ledger also work correctly because they read from persisted state. Fix: replace `agentResult?.toolResult ?? null` with `persistToolResult` in the `verdict:parsed` emit.","line":765}],"observations":[{"severity":"low","file":"src/core/step/executor.ts","title":"Redundant `|| isConformanceStep` in the scope-check guard","rationale":"`isJudgeStep` is defined as `JUDGE_REPORT_TOOL || CODE_REVIEW_REPORT_TOOL || isConformanceStep`, so the guard `(isJudgeStep || isConformanceStep)` is algebraically equivalent to `isJudgeStep`. No functional defect today, but a future reader might conclude that the two conditions are independently meaningful and introduce a real divergence. Simplifying to `isJudgeStep` would remove the ambiguity.","line":659},{"severity":"low","file":"src/core/pipeline/scope.ts","title":"No runtime guard that `checkpoint` names a judge-typed step","rationale":"If a future profile declares `permissionScope.checkpoint` pointing to a non-judge step (e.g. `design`), the executor's `(isJudgeStep || isConformanceStep)` guard silently suppresses the scope check — no error, no log, no escalation. The design documents the constraint (D1/D5) and there is currently no profile that exercises this. A startup-time validation (or at least a warning log) when `permissionScope` is present but `checkpoint` resolves to a non-judge step would make the footgun visible. Not blocking in this PR since no profile currently declares a scope."}]},"followUpAttempts":1,"transientRetryAttempts":0},"startedAt":"2026-06-13T15:42:49.143Z","endedAt":"2026-06-13T15:50:41.349Z"}
